******
[1] Gujarat (Ahmedabad)
Date: Thu 14 Jun 2012
Source: Daily News & Analysis (DNA) [edited]
http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_few-larva-sites-yet-malaria-cases-in-a-bad-triple_1702242


If the figures in the daily health report of AMC's [Ahmedabad Municipal Corporation] health department are anything to go by, the number of malaria cases has tripled in just one year. The city, in January-May 2011, had reported 946 cases on the vector-borne disease, which has increased to 3047 in the same period this year [2012].

Interestingly, a recent survey conducted by the health department indicates that Ahmedabad has lower density of mosquitoes from last year, but malaria is prevalent! The larvae index survey was conducted to identify areas with high mosquito breeding and hence tackle the problem of rising cases of malaria. Ranip and Kali have the highest larvae index followed by Girdharnagar, Naroda Road, and Chandlodia.

"Larvae indices of Ranip and Kali are as high as 1.8. For every 1000 houses, there are 18 with mosquito larvae breeding in them," said an official with the health department, requesting anonymity.

Vejalpur, which was most prone to mosquito breeding till last year [2011], has emerged as the area with the lowest density this year. The average larvae index of Ahmedabad stands at 0.9 with Vejalpur recording the lowest density at 0.2. This means that only 2 houses out of 1000 in Vejalpur have mosquito larvae.

Girdharnagar and Naroda road recorded larvae indices of 1.6 and 1.3 respectively. Mosquito larvae breed in stagnant water, said the official. "Many of the slums and people of middle income group tend to store water in large containers for weeks, which lead to breeding of mosquitoes. Our team of health officials checked for such sites and treated the stored water with temephos solution to prevent breeding," added the official. Water stagnant for more than 7 days is a favourable breeding ground for mosquito larvae. "If residents want to store water, then the best method is to cover the container with an air-tight lid or tie a cloth on the mouth of the water container to avoid mosquito breeding," said official.

[Byline: Chaitra Devarhubli]

